Airport.Name: Chicago O'Hare Intl
Report.Status: Probable Cause
the arcing of the windshield heat system at the upper, aft (J1) and upper, forward (J4) terminal locations on the first officer's windshield, which caused the inner pane of glass to fracture.

Airport.Name: Austin Bergstrom International
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain control of the airplane while parked on the ramp with the engine running.

Airport.Name: St. Augustine
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to adhere to the controller's takeoff instruction.  Contributing to the incident was the controller's failure to properly monitor the flight, and the controller's decision to perform lesser duty priorities during the takeoff roll.

Airport.Name: Washington Reagan
Report.Status: Inadequate ground separation maintained by the pilot of the Embraer E170.

Airport.Name: Austin Bergstrom International
Report.Status: The airplane struck a large bird while making a visual approach to the airport.

Airport.Name: QUAD-CITY
Report.Status: The arcing of the resistor and silicone controlled rectifier in the flap control circuit.

Airport.Name: Jackson Hole
Report.Status: the loss of braking action on the left main landing gear due to the cross connection of the wheel speed tachometer wires that was caused by inadequate maintenance performed on the airplane during the installation of the main landing gear.

Airport.Name: DALLAS LOVE FIELD
Report.Status: The failure of the taxiing flight crew to maintain an adequate clearance from the stationary airplane.

The installed wing panel clips failed due to fatigue, likely caused by the incorrect installation of the fasteners in response to SB 757-57-0027.  Contributing to the incorrect installation was the SB's lack of clarity in the instructions and figures on the correct orientation of the clips and spacers.

Airport.Name: West 30th St. Heliport
Report.Status: The pilot's inadequate visual lookout and subsequent failure to maintain clearance from the other helicopter due to his focus on the engine instruments during the initial departure. Contributing to the accident was insufficient helipad spacing.

Airport.Name: Page Municipal
Report.Status: The flight crews unprofessional behavior and deviation from standard operating procedures which resulted in an in-flight emergency.

Airport.Name: George Bush Intercontinental
Report.Status: The flight crew's improper landing technique for an inoperative anti-skid system resulting in locked brakes and four blown main landing gear tires.

Airport.Name: PORTLAND-HILLSBORO
Report.Status: The malfunction of the airplane's battery and alternator that resulted in the failure of the landing gear to extend and lock in place.

Airport.Name: Erie Muncipal Airport
Report.Status: the pilot's failure to maintain directional control during landing.  A contributing factor was the gusty wind conditions.

Airport.Name: Kelly's Island
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain aircraft control during landing.  Contributing to the accident were the pilot's selection of the wrong runway and a tailwind.

Airport.Name: Newark Liberty International
Report.Status: An engine fire in the No. 3 engine due to the failure of, and subsequent flammable fluid leak from, one of three fuel or hydraulic lines located in the engine's accessory raceway that ignited when the fluid came in contact with the hot engine cases.  Contributing to the incident were the lack of adequate inspection and test requirements and appropriate life limit or inspection interval requirements by the manufacturer.

Airport.Name: Singapore Changi Airport
Report.Status: The Center Landing gear (CLG) strut failed due to intergranular (IG) cracking resulted from a contamination of the surface from the chemical used to clean that area prior to painting.

Airport.Name: Garner Field Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's excessive speed during a turn off the active runway to the taxiway which exceeded the lateral limits of the supporting landing gear structure resulting in the collapse of the left main gear.
The pilot's inadequate weather evaluation during the landing approach. Contributing to the accident were windshear and rocky terrain.

Airport.Name: Hollister Municipal
Report.Status: The failure of the pilot of the other airplane to maintain physical clearance while taxiing.

The insufficient predicted fatigue life of the P/N KBE6-59 adjustable-length 3/8-inch rod end, and the inadequate fatigue margin at the transcowl CDU clevis assembly bracket attachment rivets for the one actuator out condition, which resulted in the failure of a second transcowl attachment during thrust reverser activation, leading to the partial liberation of the thrust reversers inboard transcowl.
The directional control of the parachute not obtained/maintained by the pilot during the takeoff roll. A contributing factor was separation of the nose landing gear.

Airport.Name: Orlando Sanford Int. Airport
Report.Status: A failure of the nose landing gear strut weldment.

Airport.Name: Wharton Regional Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain aircraft control.

Airport.Name: Phoenix Sky Harbor Intl.
Report.Status: The failure of the MLG was due to cracking in the cylinder wall resulting from a fatigue mechanism which initiated at, and near the inner diameter (ID) surface, with propagation through the wall toward the outer diameter(OD) surface. Crack initiation was due to base metal damage which took the form of over tempered martensite (OTM) and chemical attack/pitting of the base metal.

Airport.Name: Chicago Midway International
Report.Status: The inadvertent partial inflation of the evacuation slide within the tailcone during takeoff and subsequent binding of the elevator control cables. The partial inflation resulted from the tailcone evacuation slide cover failing to be secured to the floor fittings on the walkway for undetermined reasons.

Airport.Name: Doctor's Hospital Heliport
Report.Status: The lack of available engine power and subsequent loss of rotor rpm due to the pilots departing with one engine at idle. Contributing to the incident was a corroded engine control wiring harness.

Air.carrier: North American Jet Charters Group, LLC
Report.Status: The improper installation of the forward edge of the left-hand wing-to-body panel, causing the fairing to separate from the airplane during an in-flight encounter with light turbulence. Contributing to the event was the use of small-head screws and grommets in securing the fairing.

Airport.Name: REID-HILLVIEW OF SANTA CLARA C
Report.Status: The inadequate visual lookout of the pilot and his failure to maintain clearance from another airplane.

Airport.Name: Salinas Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's inability to maintain directional control due to the fatigue failure of the threaded portion of the forward directional control cable as a result of the improper installation a lock washer.

Airport.Name: Denver International
Report.Status: Total failure of the right inboard tire. Contributing to this incident were the low pressure of the tire, and the high tire heat generated by the previous rejected takeoff.
The impact with a bird during initial takeoff climb.
The pilots encounter with high winds during approach. Contributing to the severity of injuries was the passengers' improper landing preparation.
The improper assembly of the governor during manufacture.

Airport.Name: La Porte Municipal Airport
Report.Status: A loss of engine power due to fuel exhaustion as a result of siphoning from the fuel filler neck and cap. Contributing to the incident were the fuel over-servicing which resulted in the siphoning condition, and the ASTM standards which allowed for the fuel tank filler neck/vent design.

Airport.Name: Mark's Park and Airfield
Report.Status: The pilot's loss of directional control during landing due to failure of the nose wheel support as a result of an inadequate weld.
The pilot's improper fuel management, resulting in fuel exhaustion and the subsequent hard landing.

Airport.Name: O'Hare International Airport
Report.Status: The failure of an electrical relay due to eroded contacts and the flight crew's decision to continue a flight that was operating on battery power.

Airport.Name: Queen City Airport
Report.Status: The fatigue failure of a blade in the second-stage turbine wheel, which resulted in a total loss of engine power.

Airport.Name: Chicago Midway
Report.Status: The right nose landing gear axle's failure from intergranular and fatigue cracking due to an earlier bearing failure.

Airport.Name: Lakeland Linder Regional Apt.
Report.Status: A failure of the flap actuator rod end due to low stress, high cycle fatigue, and subsequent overstress failure.

Air.carrier: California Shock and Trauma Air Rescue
Report.Status: The failure of the vertical stabilizer control adapter due to reverse bending fatigue.
The failure of the vertical stabilizer control adapter due to reverse bending fatigue.

Airport.Name: Glendale Municipal
Report.Status: The Kitfox's pilot's failure to ascertain if the intersection he approached was clear of conflicting traffic and the controller's failure to provide pertinent traffic advisories to both pilots. Contributing to the accident was the reduced visibility from the cockpits of the conventional gear airplanes.

Airport.Name: Cambridge-Dorchester Airport
Report.Status: The failure of the RV-6A's right brake assembly o-ring due to excessive heat.

Airport.Name: Salt Lake City Int.
Report.Status: The tug driver's failure to maintain situational awareness during the push back operation.

Airport.Name: Lubbock Preston Smith Int'l
Report.Status: An unidentified anomaly within the airplane's electrical system.  Contributing to the incident was the pilot's failure to manually extend the landing gear.

Airport.Name: Fairbanks International
Report.Status: The failure of the instructor in the Cessna 152 to maintain separation from another landing airplane and his failure to follow the tower controllers instructions.

Airport.Name: Philadelphia International
Report.Status: The mechanical overload of the nosewheel steering links for undetermined reasons, which resulted in nose landing gear rotation and its subsequent wedging within the wheel well structure.

Airport.Name: Greenville Spartanburg
Report.Status: The overheating and arcing of the DC Ground Service Relay and Block Diodes component for undetermined reasons.

Airport.Name: Fort Lauderdale/Hollywood Int
Report.Status: The airplane manufacturer's inadequate inspection procedure resulting in undetected fatigue cracking of the main landing gear barrel of the upper barrel and trunnion assembly.

Airport.Name: Meacham International Airport
Report.Status: Collision with a hidden obstruction while taxiing through a grass field following a forced landing. Contributing to the accident was a loss of engine power due to the pilot's failure to turn on the carburetor heat.

Airport.Name: Philadelphia International
Report.Status: the failure of the maintenance personnel to properly complete the installation, and the inspection personnel to conduct the proper functional test, of the left main landing gear uplock assembly.

Airport.Name: Chicago O'Hare International
Report.Status: The failure of the left landing gear to extend due to improper maintenance when the landing gear door was replaced. Contributing to the incident was the manufacturer's inadequate maintenance manual instructions.

Airport.Name: Hapuna Heliport
Report.Status: The separation of the endplate bolts for undetermined reasons, resulting in an in-flight separation of the right endplate. Contributing to the accident was the manufacturer's failure to provide sufficient guidance for endplate bolt installation.

Airport.Name: Atlanta International Airport
Report.Status: The fan blade fractured due to a fatigue crack that was the result of the combination of the breakdown of the fan blade lubrication system and residual fatigue life usage following the last overhaul of the fan blade.  Contributing to the fracture was the inadequate lubrication schedule established by the engine manufacturer that was not reflective of the operators use of the engine.
None.

Airport.Name: Weiser Air Park
Report.Status: Both pilot's failure to see and avoid the other aircraft.
The pilot's failure to maintain a safe rate of descent during landing.  Contributing to the accident was the strong surface winds.

Airport.Name: Aspen-Pitkin County Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's inability to maintain directional control of the airplane during landing for undetermined reasons.

Airport.Name: Fairmont State Airfield
Report.Status: Both pilots' failure to see and avoid the other aircraft.

Airport.Name: Salt Lake City Int. Airport
Report.Status: The flight crew's failure to maintain clearance from the stationary vehicle while taxiing.

Airport.Name: Tucson International Airport
Report.Status: The flight instructors inadequate situational awareness while taxiing that led to an encounter with jet blast.
A loss of engine power due to the failure of the number three engine bearing as a result of oil starvation due to coked oil obstructing the oil passages.
An inadvertent in-flight collision with a duck.

Airport.Name: Company Helipad
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain clearance from the parked helicopter.

Failure of the low pressure turbine stage 3 disk due to a design that is vulnerable to high pressure turbine unbalance-induced synchronous vibration that cannot  be detected in flight, and the subsequent uncontained engine failure.

Airport.Name: Hartsfield Jackson Int. Arpt
Report.Status: The flight attendants failure to properly restrain herself after taking her jumpseat.

The formation and propagation of a fatigue crack in the trailing edge of the main rotor blade due to interconnected porosity and resultant corrosion. The area of interconnected porosity was due to a manufacturing defect which was not detected during the manufacturing process.
Inadequate torque on one of the No. 6 connecting rod bolt retaining nuts, which resulted in the connecting rods separation from the crankshaft and a subsequent total loss of engine power.

Airport.Name: Camarillo
Report.Status: The cruise flight separation of the canopy door.  Contributing to the incident was the pilot's failure to ensure that the left side door was securely closed prior to takeoff.
The pilot's failure to attain/maintain adequate airspeed to become airborne within the distance available for takeoff.
Undetermined.
The pilot's failure to gain sufficient altitude during the takeoff in order to avoid contacting the cameraman.  Contributing to the accident was the pilot's lack of experience.
The pilot's failure to maintain clearance from the power lines.

Airport.Name: Nantucket Memo Airport
Report.Status: Installation of an improper bearing in the landing gear actuator.

Airport.Name: Danville Airport
Report.Status: The student pilot's failure to maintain control during a landing.

Airport.Name: William P. Hobby Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's inadvertent application of excessive braking after touchdown, which caused the right wheels to lock and several tires to blow and resulted in a subsequent brake fire.

Airport.Name: Taoyuan International Airport

Report.Status: A total loss of engine power due to the failure of the No. 2 piston as a result of a fatigue crack of undetermined origin.

Airport.Name: Denver International Airport
Report.Status: There was a malfunction of the electronic engine control (EEC) burner pressure (Pb) sensor that had an abnormally high indication that resulted in an excessive amount of fuel being pumped into the engine that was still at a sub-idle condition.  Because the engine was still accelerating to idle, the limited airflow through the engine engine was insufficient for the amount of fuel and resulted in a tailpipe fire.  The cause of the EEC's Pb sensor fault could not be determined.

Airport.Name: Hartsfield Jackson ATL Inter.
Report.Status: The failure of the left main landing gear to extend due to high levels of particulate contamination in the hydraulic fluid.
A hard landing as a result of unexpected high winds and gusts.

Airport.Name: West Desert Airpark
Report.Status: The pilot inadvertently applied the tow release handle.

Airport.Name: Put In Bay Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain directional control while landing with a crosswind.

Airport.Name: Midland Airpark
Report.Status: The pilots failure to ensure the airplane was properly configured, which resulted in a wheels-up landing.

Airport.Name: Douglas International
Report.Status: The failure of the left hand main landing gear was caused by heat induced cracks resulting from abusive grinding/polishing of the chrome plate that was applied during the last overhaul.

Airport.Name: Sugar Land Municipal AIrport
Report.Status: The failure of the spinner following an unavoidable bird strike. Contributing to the incident were the inadequate engine bird strike certification requirements in place at the time the engine was certified.
an inadvertent encounter with convective turbulence.

Airport.Name: Lake Hood Seaplane Base
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to remain clear of the propeller after starting the float-equipped airplane's engine by hand-propping.

Airport.Name: Caddo Mills Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The failure of the operator to ensure that the airplane engine was shutdown during passenger unloading and the lack of adequate supervision of the passenger by the pilot and ground crewmember.

Airport.Name: Lynden Pindling International
Report.Status: failure of the engine high pressure turbine active clearance control valve fuel rod supply tube coupling seal due to a cross-threaded B-nut as installed during original manufacture.

Airport.Name: Sugar Land Regional Airport
Report.Status: The improper installation of the pitch trim cable which resulted in it making improper contact with a guard pin that led to the fatigue failure of the cable.

Airport.Name: Louisa County/Freeman Field
Report.Status: The Cessna pilot's inadequate visual lookout.

Airport.Name: Los Angeles International
Report.Status: The failure of the right main landing gear inboard axle due to fatigue cracking as a result of fretting damage in one of the brake mounting bolt holes.

Airport.Name: Newark Liberty Airport
Report.Status: Failure of Main Landing Gear (MLG) truck beam was due to contamination of the inner surface corrosion protective layers from hydraulic fluid and deice fluid that resulted in corrosion and intergranular stress corrosion cracking.
The complete loss of engine power due to failure of the number two connecting rod.  The reason for the connecting rod failure could not be determined.

Airport.Name: Albuquerque Intl Sunport
Report.Status: The pilots failure to maintain adequate clearance from a known obstacle and the pilots failure to maintain control of the balloon during the sudden climb following the ejection of the passenger.

Airport.Name: Albuquerque Intl Airport
Report.Status: The pilots failure to maintain control of the balloon during the approach and landing.

Airport.Name: Albuquerque Intl Sunport
Report.Status: The pilots failure to select an adequate landing area.

Airport.Name: Lincoln Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The right landing gear's partial retraction during landing due to paint contamination of the landing gear handle detent.

Airport.Name: Show Low Regional Airport
Report.Status: An in-flight collision with a bird during initial descent.

Airport.Name: Greene County-Lewis A. Jackson
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain the proper glide slope during final approach, which resulted in an in-flight collision with a tree.
The loss of engine power due to component failure from excessive heating of the engine connecting rod journals.

Airport.Name: Kansas City International
Report.Status: The in-flight engine ingestion of one or more Lesser Snow Geese (Chen caerulescens caerulescens).

Airport.Name: Lake Elmo Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's delay in aborting the takeoff during the takeoff roll when he became aware of the engine not producing full power.

Airport.Name: Blue Grass Airport
Report.Status: The overstress failure of the nose landing gear aft drag brace.

Airport.Name: Charlotte Douglas Intl
Report.Status:
The Captain's failure to initiate a go-around from a Category III approach when satisfactory tracking performance was not maintained below the required altitude resulting in excessive bank angle maneuvers at low altitude.
 
Factors contributing to the incident were:  The Captain's decision to execute a Category III autoland approach on a runway without rollout guidance contrary to company Flight Manual guidance, the Captain's decision to deviate from the Category III approach and continue it manually contrary to the company Operating Manual, and the First Officer's failure to call for a go-around when the approach became unstable.

Airport.Name: Dallas/Fort Worth Internationa
Report.Status: A fatigue failure of an elevator stop bracket, which resulted in a partial jam of the elevator control. Contributing to the failure was the improper installation of shim stacks, poor alignment of the brackets, and cyclic stresses acting on the lower stop, generated by the repeated improper use of the gust lock system.

Airport.Name: Cincinnati International Airpo
Report.Status: Failure of the NLG cylinder occurred by intergranular rupture; coincidental to a chrome plating crack. The failure origin occurred along the inner surface of the cylinder and then propagated by stress corrosion cracking to the outer surface. A secondary crack with the same features as the primary crack was found diagonal to the primary crack. Both cracks initiated by intergranular cracking due to grinding burns caused by abusive grinding and propagated by stress corrosion cracking. Hydrogen embrittlement did not contribute to the intergranular cracking.

Airport.Name: Newark
Report.Status:
A mechanical failure of internal components of the right main landing gear door actuator resulting in the flight crew being unable to fully extend the right main landing gear using the normal and alternate procedures.

Contributing to this incident was a circular reference in the company Flight Manual in which the Landing Gear Gravity Extension checklist referred back to the Landing Gear Unsafe Indication After Extension checklist rather than the Landing Gear - Partial Gear or Gear Up Landing checklist.

Airport.Name: Henry E Rohlsen Airport
Report.Status: The sealing failure between the fuel nozzle adapter assembly and fuel transfer tubes that allowed fuel to leak into the nacelle fire zone where it was subsequently ignited by the hot combustor case. Contributing to the failure was a combination of manufacturing defects of the fuel nozzle adapter assembly by the manufacturer and incorrectly overhauled fuel transfer tubes by the engine manufacturer. Contributing to the incident was a second defect of the fuel nozzle adapter assembly by the manufacturer which prevented maintenance personnel from detecting the internal fuel leak.

Airport.Name: Yeager Airport
Report.Status: (1) The flight crewmembers unprofessional behavior, including their nonadherence to sterile cockpit procedures by engaging in nonpertinent conversation, which distracted them from their primary flight-related duties and led to their failure to correctly set and verify the flaps; (2) the captains decision to reconfigure the flaps during the takeoff roll instead of rejecting the takeoff when he first identified the misconfiguration, which resulted in the rejected takeoff beginning when the airplane was about 13 knots above the takeoff decision speed and the subsequent runway overrun; and (3) the flight crewmembers lack of checklist discipline, which contributed to their failure to detect the incorrect flap setting before initiating the takeoff roll. Contributing to the survivability of this incident was the presence of an engineered materials arresting system beyond the runway end.

Airport.Name: Juanda Airport
Los Angeles International
Report.Status: The flight crews failure to maintain clearance from the jet bridge during taxi. Contributing to the incident was the ramp marshaller's diverted attention and failure to signal the flight crew to stop at the correct position.
an inadvertent encounter with clear air turbulence.

Airport.Name: Nashville International
Report.Status: A loss of engine power due to the mechanics failure to properly secure the fuel control unit fuel lines after replacement of the starter adapter.

Airport.Name: Minneapolis-St Paul Intl
Report.Status: The pilot not setting the parking brake adequately while holding for departure.  Contributing to the accident was the pilot being distracted while doing his paperwork.

Airport.Name: Republic Airport
Report.Status: Progressive cracking from an undetermined initiation source, which resulted in the failure of the No. 4 cabin window outer pane, and the subsequent foreign object ingestion to the right engine.

Airport.Name: Chicago O'Hare IAP
Report.Status: An in-flight encounter with lightning. Contributing to the incident was the damaged and displaced tailcone bulkhead frame that inhibited the full travel of the elevator during approach.

Airport.Name: Air Logistics Galliano
Report.Status: An unsecured access door, which departed the helicopter and damaged a main rotor blade and a tail rotor blade. Contributing to the incident was the helicopter's color scheme, which made visual inspection of the door difficult.

Airport.Name: Newark International Airport
Report.Status: The separation of both halves of the left engine fan cowl assembly due to improper latching and locking of the all the fan cowl latches. The cause of the improper latching and locking of the fan cowls was due to the failure of the mechanic to unstow and properly latch and lock the fan cowl latches after the engine maintenance had been completed, and the failure of the maintenance  inspector to detect and identify the unlatched condition. Contributing the incident is the design of the fan cowl latch assembly that can provide a false latch condition when the latch is neither latched or locked. Also contributing incident is the lack of adequate Airbus and Jet Blue fan cowl latch inspection guidance to detect and identify an unlatched condition.
A failure of the pilot's side window due to undetected cracking around the lower aft portion of the storm window cutout.

Airport.Name: Washington Dulles
Report.Status:
The ignition of the J5 power terminal located on the captains No. 1 windshield due to a loose electrical connection between the terminal connector lug and its respective terminal block. The loose connection resulted from a missing lock washer that allowed the resistance in the electrical path to increase sufficiently to generate high enough temperatures to ignite the terminal block.

Contributing to the probable cause was the lack of instructions to ensure the lock washer was installed in the J5 power terminal block in the Boeing 757 aircraft maintenance manual (AMM). 

Additionally, contributing to the incident was the deferral of the related maintenance write-up before the incident, which resulted from information in the United Airlines AMM that stated, When bus bar(s) show signs of blackening or burning, the condition is acceptable for continued service, although the window must be replaced within 50 flight-hours.

Airport.Name: Ontario International Airport
Report.Status: Failure of the airplanes nose landing gear to extend for undetermined reasons.

Airport.Name: Mc Kinley Field
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to see and avoid the power lines.

Airport.Name: Westchester County Airport
Report.Status: The flight crew's failure to ensure that the cabin door was secured/locked prior to takeoff.

Airport.Name: Landers Loop - Dover, Arkansas
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain clearance from the trees during takeoff.

Airport.Name: Charlotte/Douglas Internationa
Report.Status: The Airbus A330 flight crew's failure to maintain clearance from a standing airplane while taxiing.

A suspected failure of the tail rotor for undetermined reasons. A contributing factor was the failure of the emergency floats to properly inflate due to improper installment and inspection by maintenance personnel.

Airport.Name: Eleftherios Venizelos Internat
Report.Status: A short circuit involving the light in position L3 on the squib test panel.  The specific cause of the short circuit could not be determined.
The pilots failure to maintain control of the balloon during landing.

Airport.Name: Jundiai Airport
Air.carrier: Government Of the State Of Amazon

Airport.Name: Moraine Air Park
Report.Status: The unintentional movement of the jettison handle in-flight due to the pilots dropping of a manual that impacted the handle and released the door window, which then impacted the horizontal stabilizer. Contributing to the accident was the jettison handle guard not being installed by maintenance personnel.

Improper reassembly of the collective flight controls by maintenance personnel. Contributing to the incident were inadequate postmaintenance examinations by maintenance personnel and inadequate preflight inspections by two pilots.

Airport.Name: Hartsfield-Jackson Atlanta Int
Report.Status: The cause of the right wing landing light switch fire is undetermined.

Airport.Name: South Timbalier 178A
Report.Status: The loss of main rotor rpm during takeoff for reasons that could not be determined because postaccident examination of the airframe and engine did not reveal any anomalies.

Airport.Name: Barnstable Municipal
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to extend the landing gear prior to landing flare and touchdown.

Airport.Name: Luis Munoz Marin International
Report.Status: The airplane manufacturers inadequate inspection procedures, resulting in the undetected fatigue cracking of the right upper barrel and trunnion assembly.
The inability of either pilot to see the other airplane due to the blind spot created by their respective airplane's wings.

Airport.Name: Charles M Schulz-Sonoma County
Report.Status: The failure of the pilot to maintain clearance from another airplane while taxiing.

Airport.Name: CHICAGO O'HARE INTL
Report.Status: the brake fire after landing was caused by hydraulic fluid leaking on to hot brakes.
The fracture of the collective servo actuator piston rod resulting from stress corrosion cracking.

Airport.Name: Sacramento International
Report.Status: The first officers inadvertent activation of the parking brake in flight, which led to the airplane abruptly stopping and all four of its main landing gear tires deflating, and his use of a nonstandard procedure to cancel the airplane's monitoring alert system.

Airport.Name: Central Illinois Regional
Air.carrier: IMAGE AIR OF SOUTHWEST FLORIDA LC
Report.Status: The cracked nose landing gear fork assembly found during the preflight inspection.
The balloon's encounter with an updraft, resulting in an immediate landing and an intentional collision with a tree.

Airport.Name: Brenham Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The pilots decision to depart with a known failed brake control unit.

Location: John F. Kennedy International Airport, NY
Airport.Name: John F. Kennedy International
Report.Status: The probable cause of the incident was the restriction of the right main landing gear door against the fuselage wheel well body fairing which prevented the extension of the right main landing gear.

Airport.Name: GENERAL MITCHELL INTL
Report.Status: The failure of the left main landing gear (MLG) to extend normally and manually for reasons that could not be conclusively determined.

Airport.Name: Idaho Falls Regional
Report.Status: The partial retraction/collapse of the main landing gear during the landing roll for undetermined reasons.

Airport.Name: Teterboro Airport
Report.Status: The pilot-in-command's failure to attain the proper touchdown point while landing with a gusting crosswind and failure to initiate a go-around, which resulted in a landing more than halfway down the runway and a subsequent runway overrun. Contributing to the incident was the failure of either pilot to call for a go-around when the airplane was at Vref plus 15 at 50 feet above the runway or once they had floated well beyond the touchdown zone of the runway.

Airport.Name: Ft. Lauderdale International
Report.Status: The flightcrews failure to maintain directional control while initiating an engine reverse after landing.

Airport.Name: Phoenix Sky Harbor Intl.
Report.Status: The overextension of the main cabin door due to difficulty opening the door because the power-assist motor cable was lodged within the main cabin door assembly.

Airport.Name: Hilton Head AIrport
Report.Status: The Pitts pilot's inadequate visual lookout and failure to maintain clearance from the Cirrus airplane.

Airport.Name: Frankfurt
Madras Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The failure of both pilots to see and avoid the other airplane while in the traffic pattern to land, which resulted in a midair collision.

Airport.Name: Brigham & Women's Hospital
Report.Status: Improper installation of wiring associated with a medical cabinet interior, which resulted in chafing and a subsequent in-flight fire. Contributing to the incident was inadequate maintenance procedures for continued airworthiness.

Airport.Name: USAF Academy Airfield
Report.Status: Fatigue failure of the nose wheel fork, which resulted in separation of the nose wheel.

Airport.Name: Mineral Wells Airport
Report.Status: A total loss of engine power in flight due to a loss of engine oil for reasons that could not be determined during a postaccident teardown examination of the engine.
